    <section>
      <title>Changing Work Habit</title>
      <chapter>
        <title>Digital Revolution</title>
        <paragraph>For several decades there has been a clear distinction between the time for labour and the time of leisure. The technological development increases the productivity but also the time people spend doing work stuff.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>Today, thanks to the advances in computing power, thanks to the "Internet of Things" which allows the connection of devices, items and humans, the new paradigm of work called "Smartworking" enables people to handle many jobs at home and in public spaces.</paragraph>
      </chapter>
      <chapter>
        <title>The Gig Economy</title>
        <paragraph>These new condictions led people to build another level of job in which the arrival of electronics and computer science have assumed a crucial role.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>The advanced robotics and autonomous transport, the "Artificial Intelligence" and "Machine Learning" have changed the world of work in terms of features and numbers. An example: despite the creation of millions of new jobs over the next 4 years, there will likely be a net loss of $ 5 million.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>In the near future everything we will do will be generating data and lots of data is exactly what machines will need in order to learn to learn.</paragraph>
      </chapter>
      <chapter>
        <title>Post-Work Economy</title>
        <paragraph>Yet in 2013 An Oxford University study estimated the potential automation of about half of all existing jobs by 2033.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>The future of employment will be robots. What’s more, humans are entirely unprepared. These exponential advances will prove daunting for as long as we continue to insist upon employment as our primary source of income. But robots are never going to take all the jobs. The problem with trying to envision "a world without work" is that it asks us to envision an unrealistically large change. The more likely outcome is a world with less work. And that's a world we should welcome rather than fear. It's a world in which we can make some policy decisions we want to make, rather than decisions we really don't want to make. It's a world in which the shorter day work is a necessity in productivity and well-being.</paragraph>
        <paragraph>it's a world not so far in which we must seriously start talking about decoupling income from work, adopting a universal basic income.</paragraph>
      </chapter>
